Q1. (Exercise 4.6)

  1. We see that the sampling distribution is normally distributed, with the estimate mean at 0.315 with estimate standard error being 0.0922

  2. Using the following equation \(SE = \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}} = \sqrt{\frac{0.316(1-0.316)}{25}} = 0.09298258\) we get that theoretical standard error to be 0.09298258. This is relatively close to our initial 0.092 estimated standard error

set.seed(69420)
Recidivism <- read.csv("https://sites.google.com/site/chiharahesterberg/data2/Recidivism.csv")
N <- 10^4
phat <- numeric(N)
for (i in 1:N)
{
  samp <- sample(Recidivism$Recid, 25)
  phat[i] <- mean(samp == "Yes")
}
hist(phat, freq = FALSE, main = NULL, breaks = 30)

mean(phat) #0.315
## [1] 0.317352
sd(phat) #0.092
## [1] 0.09227394
  1. Using the following equation \(SE = \sqrt{\frac{\hat p (1 - \hat p)}{n}} = \sqrt{\frac{0.316(1-0.316)}{250}} = 0.02940367\) we get that theoretical standard error to be 0.02940367. This pair of theoretical standard error and estimated standard error is closer than the previous one with n = 25 cases.
set.seed(69420)
Recidivism <- read.csv("https://sites.google.com/site/chiharahesterberg/data2/Recidivism.csv")
N <- 10^4
phat <- numeric(N)
for (i in 1:N)
{
  samp <- sample(Recidivism$Recid, 250)
  phat[i] <- mean(samp == "Yes")
}
hist(phat, freq = FALSE, main = NULL, breaks = 30)

mean(phat) 
## [1] 0.3169336
sd(phat) 
## [1] 0.02905113

sd(FlightDelays$Delay)
## [1] 41.6305
  1. Looking at the histogram below, we see that the simulated sampling distribution is skewed to the right, We get an estimated mean of 11.64506 and a standard error 8.281396.
set.seed(69420)
FlightDelays <- read.csv("https://sites.google.com/site/chiharahesterberg/data2/FlightDelays.csv")

  1. Our estimated standard error of 8.281396 is very far off from our theoretical standard error of 0.6558627
TSE <- sd(FlightDelays$Delay)/sqrt(4029)
TSE
## [1] 0.6558627
  1. Our estimated standard erorr is now 2.53198, which is much closer to the theoretical standard error of 0.6558627 compared to when n = 25

Q3. (Exercise 4.12)

Looking at the calculations below, we see that \(P(\hat X \leq 4.6) = 0.02385744\)

n <- 20
mean <- 6
variance <- 10
val <- (4.6 - 6)/(sqrt(10)/sqrt(20))
pnorm(val)
## [1] 0.02385744

Q4. (Exercise 4.20)

  1. \[E(\bar Z) = E(\bar X) - E(\bar Y) = 7 - 10 = -3\] \[Var(\bar Z) = Var(\bar X) + Var(\bar Y) = \frac{3^2}{9} + \frac{5^2}{12} = 1 - \frac{37}{12} = -\frac{37}{12} \approx 3.083\] Because of the Central Limit Theorem, we can get that \(W \sim N(-3, 3.083)\)

  2. We get simulated mean and standard error as -3.046 and 3.051, these are close to the theoretical mean and stdard error of -3 and 3.083

set.seed(69420)
W <- numeric(1000)
for (i in 1:1000)
{
x <- rnorm(9,7,3)
y <- rnorm(12,10,5)
W[i] <- mean(x) - mean(y)
}
hist(W)

mean(W)
## [1] -3.046227
sum((W - mean(W))^2/ length(W))
## [1] 3.050577
  1. We get that \(P(W < -1.5) = 0.82\), our exact answer is 0.804, which is pretty close to our estimated answer
prob<- (-1.5 + 3)/(sqrt(3.083))
bleh <- pnorm(prob)
bleh
## [1] 0.8035274
mean(W < -1.5)
## [1] 0.82

Q5. (Exercise 4.14)

We get the probability that between 220 and 230 people, 29.6% of people will have a high school diploma

n <- 800
p <- 0.286
pbinom(220, 800, 0.286)
## [1] 0.259103
pbinom(230, 800, 0.286)
## [1] 0.5550674
pbinom(230, 800, 0.286) - pbinom(220, 800, 0.286)
## [1] 0.2959644

Q6. (Exercise 4.28)

\[f(x) = 3x^2\] \[P(X \leq x) = \int_0^x3x^2dx\] \[P(X \leq x) = x^3\] a) \[f(x_{min}) = n[1-x_{1}^n]^{n-1}f(x_n)\] \[f(x_{min}) = n[1-x_1^3]^{n-1}3x_n^2\] \[f(x_{min}) = 3n[1-x_1^3]^{n-1}x_n^2 (0 \leq x \leq 1)\] b) \[f(x_{max}) = n[f(x_n)]^{n-1}f(x_n)\] \[f(x_{max}) = 3n \cdot x_n^{n-1}x_n^2\] \[f(x_{max}) = 3n \cdot x_n^{3n-1} (0 \leq x_n \leq 1)\] c) \[P[x_{max} > 0.92] = \int_{0.92}^13 \cdot 10x_n^{3 \cdot 10 -1}dx_n\] \[...\]

\[P[x_{max} > 0.92] = 1 - (0.92)^{30}\]

Q7. (Exercise 5.9)

  1. The plot seems normally distributed with the estimated mean at 24 and estimated standard error at 0.688
set.seed(69420)
sm <- numeric(1000)
for (i in 1:1000)
{
sm[i] = mean(rgamma(200,6,0.25))
}
plot(sm)

mean(sm)
## [1] 24.00057
sd(sm)
## [1] 0.6880968
  1. We get a slightly right skewed histogram with estimated mean at 24 and estimated standard error at 9.8
set.seed(69420)
samp <- rgamma(200,6,0.25)
hist(samp)

mean(samp)
## [1] 24.09766
sd(samp)
## [1] 10.22827
  1. Bootstrap mean is 24 and standard error is 0.221
set.seed(69420)
sm1 <- numeric(1000)
for (i in 1:1000)
{
sm1[i] = mean(rgamma(2000,6,0.25))
}
mean(sm1)
## [1] 24.00756
sd(sm1)
## [1] 0.2205201
  1. The mean for sampling distribution and bootstrap distribution are very close (approximately 24 for both). The standard error is a bit different with smapling distribution having a 0.6881 SE and bootstrap distribution having an 0.221 SE.
data.frame(
    Distribution = c("Sampling distribution", 
                     "Bootstrap distribution"), 
    Mean = c(mean(sm), mean(sm1)),
    SE = c(sd(sm), sd(sm1))
)
##             Distribution     Mean        SE
## 1  Sampling distribution 24.00057 0.6880968
## 2 Bootstrap distribution 24.00756 0.2205201
  1. As the sample size gets smaller, shilw the means stay about the same, the SE gets significantly worse and more different as sample size decreases
set.seed(69420)
sm_1 <- numeric(1000)
for (i in 1:1000)

}

Q8. (Exercise 5.11)

  1. The histogram is extremely right skewed with a boxplot that fits that as well. The summary for the chlorine consist of min = 1.00, 1st quantile = 5.00, median = 14.05, Mean = 78.31, 3rd quantile = 55.70, and max = 1550.00
set.seed(69420)
Bangladesh <- read.csv("https://sites.google.com/site/chiharahesterberg/data2/Bangladesh.csv")
Bangladesh <- na.omit(Bangladesh)
hist(Bangladesh$Chlorine)

summary(Bangladesh$Chlorine)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1.00    5.00   14.05   78.31   55.70 1550.00
boxplot(Bangladesh$Chlorine)
